<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div style="margin: 2rem 0;">
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Can I substitute ingredients in these recipes?</summary>
    <div class="faq-content">
      <p>Yes, but be careful with protein substitutions. If a recipe calls for chicken, you can use turkey or lean beef. If it calls for protein powder, stick with that - the protein content is calculated specifically for the powder amount.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>How do I know if I'm eating too fast?</summary>
    <div class="faq-content">
      <p>Common signs include: feeling uncomfortably full, nausea, pain in chest or stomach, or vomiting. Set a timer for 20-30 minutes per meal and take small bites. Put your utensil down between bites.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>What if I can't hit my protein target?</summary>
    <div class="faq-content">
      <p>This is common in the first few weeks. Focus on protein shakes and broths first. Add unflavored protein powder to soups and liquids. Track your intake and gradually increase. Consult your dietitian if consistently under 40g daily.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Can I eat these recipes if I had a different surgery (bypass vs sleeve)?</summary>
    <div class="faq-content">
      <p>Yes! These recipes work for gastric sleeve, gastric bypass, and gastric band patients. The diet stages are similar across all bariatric procedures. Always follow your specific surgeon's timeline and portion guidance.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Where can I buy protein powder in Australia?</summary>
    <div class="faq-content">
      <p>Major retailers: Chemist Warehouse, Coles, Woolworths. Online: Bulk Nutrients, Protein Supplies Australia, Amazon AU. Hospital clinics also sell medical-grade options. Look for whey protein isolate (WPI) for best absorption.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
</div>

